        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
            <p><bibl><ptr target="#gasparini-rosamilia2016"/>, n. <citedRange>5</citedRange> (fig. 21)</bibl>, whence
                <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>66.2335</citedRange></bibl>;
                <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>133700</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="divine" ref="#Eumenis"><name nymRef="#Εὐμενίς"><seg part="I">Εὐμε<unclear>νί</unclear></seg><gap reason="lost" atLeast="1" atMost="3" unit="character"/></name></persName> 
                    <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"><certainty locus="name" match=".."/></gap>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Euménide(s) <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"><certainty locus="name" match=".."/></gap>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Eumenide(s) <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"><certainty locus="name" match=".."/></gap>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Eumenide(/i) <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"><certainty locus="name" match=".."/></gap>.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
               <p>This object is unique and the lack of the name end does not help to determine its function. Although standing at a fixed place amongst altars dedicated to 
               the Eumenides (once at least one Eumenide <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr133800</ref>) it cannot support, like them, offerings. If considered nonetheless as a 
                   dedication, the formula should be completed as a dative. On the other hand, as E. Rosamilia puts it, it might also be a caption for an aniconic figure of 
                   the deity (or deities). C. Dobias-Lalou adds that it might also be a sort of sign-post for the whole area of altars. Be it what it is, the reason for the 
                   stele to be movable is not clear.</p>
	<p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
